05339nam a22006735i 9780822391395DE-B159720210225050953.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210225t20092009ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223913957 a10.1515/97808223913952doi  a(DE-B1597)554284  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHQ76.4 7aSOC0120002bisacsh04a306.76/600aHomophobias :bLust and Loathing across Time and Space /cDavid A. B. Murray. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (238 p.) :b3 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 ae-Duke books scholarly collection00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tIntroduction David -- t1 Displacing Homophobia -- t1 Can There Be an Anthropology of Homophobia? -- t2 Homophobia at New York's Gay Central -- t3 ''It's Adam and Eve, not Adam and Steve'' -- t4 The Homosexualization of Pedophilia -- t5 Stolen Kisses -- t2 Transnational Homophobias -- t6 Not Quite Redemption Song -- t7 The Emergence of Political Homophobia in Indonesia -- t8 Homo Hauntings -- t9 Lucknow Noir -- tEpilogue: What Is to Be (Un)Done? -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat is it about "the homosexual" that incites vitriolic rhetoric and violence around the world? How and why do some people hate queers? Does homophobia operate differently across social, political, and economic terrains? What are the ambivalences in homophobic discourses that can be exploited to undermine its hegemonic privilege? This volume addresses these questions through critical interrogations of sites where homophobic discourses are produced. It provides innovative analytical insights that expose the complex and intersecting cultural, political, and economic forces contributing to the development of new forms of homophobia. And it is a call to action for anthropologists and other social scientists to examine more carefully the politics, histories, and contexts of places and people who profess hatred for queerness.The contributors to this volume open up the scope of inquiry into processes of homophobia, moving the analysis of a particular form of "hate" into new, wider sociocultural and political fields. The ongoing production of homophobic discourses is carefully analyzed in diverse sites including New York City, Australia, the Caribbean, Greece, India, and Indonesia, as well as American Christian churches, in order to uncover the complex operational processes of homophobias and their intimate relationships to nationalism, sexism, racism, class, and colonialism. The contributors also critically inquire into the limitations of the term homophobia and interrogate its utility as a cross-cultural designation.Contributors. Steven Angelides, Tom Boellstorff, Lawrence Cohen, Don Kulick, Suzanne LaFont, Martin F. Manalansan IV, David A. B. Murray, Brian Riedel, Constance R. Sullivan-Blum  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / LGBT Studies / Gay Studies.2bisacsh1 aAngelides, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAngelides, Steven.1 aBoellstorff, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKulick, Don, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKulick, Don.1 aLaFont, Suzanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManalansan IV, Martin F.1 aManalansan iv, Martin F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurray, David A. B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurray, David A. B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vo